{
  "answer": "**Mirza Ghalib's ghazal opens with a couplet where *jigar* (liver)'s anatomical position below the *dil* (heart) is essential to the imagery.**[^1][^2]\n\n> **Transliteration:**  \n> Dil se teri nigāh jiagar tak utar ga'ī  \n> Donō ko ik adā meṃ razām̤and̤ kar ga'ī[^1]\n\n> **Translation:**  \n> Your glance passed from my heart into my core;  \n> With a single charm, their will to fight is gone.[^2]\n\nThe beloved's penetrating gaze travels downward through the body—from the chest's heart to the abdomen's liver—reconciling (or ravishing) both vital organs in one graceful motion (*ik adaa*). This visceral descent wouldn't land the same without *jigar*'s specific place as the body's deeper \"seat,\" evoking total emotional and physical surrender.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/35-dil-se-teri-nigaah-jigar-tak-utar-gayi/transliteration/#p-8219b3).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/35-dil-se-teri-nigaah-jigar-tak-utar-gayi/translation/#p-4ab0d4).",
